results.notes: Fruiting on a mature cherry tree near our home in Olympia, WA, USA. This same substrate(host tree) has produced fresh fruiting bodies each summer(beginning in mid to late August). Fruitings Came a bit late this year, but fresh wounds and cut locations on the tree took a bit longer for the mycelium to proliferate(from late winter to September). Images of growth added from initial observation on 9/2/19. Harvested/dehydrated a single small slice for home herbarium/voucher. We have eaten fresh, young slices from this location for the last 2 summers and they are mild and DO indeed taste akin to chicken meat. My experience with the similar species Laetiporus conifericola(fruits on conifers and is far more common here in Washington state) has always been disappointing and the flesh of that species tastes like crushed aspirin(very bitter). The hardwood fruiting sulfur shelf in the midwest(Iowa/Missouri) Laetiporus sulphureus and Laetiporus cincinnatus are mild and taste almost as good as our Laetiporus gilbertsonii.

results.notes: Two fruiting bodies on Western hemlock that I have monitored over the last month. Fruiting body on the left is at full maturity, uniformly maroon colored and covered in electrostatically dispersed spores. Fruiting body on the right is at intermediate growth stage and has not fully matured(note the triple zoned color scheme of red, yellow and pithy white growth edge). This is a perfect example of how different in appearance G. oregonense is from initial growth to full maturity. by the first frosts the fruiting body will begin to decay and lose all of the thick inner pith(eventually degrading and falling off the host tree). The entire process will begin next July with fresh fruiting bodies. Similar woody conks that are perennial(Fomitopsis, Heterobasidion, Laricifomes, etc.) remain on the host tree year after year, season after season and add a growth ring with each season(G. oregonense is an annual species and will only be found fresh for harvest in summer and early Fall).

results.notes:
This is an example of sporocarps that match the macroscopic description of Lycoperdon perlatum occurring on well-decayed wood. Most sources do not acknowledge this possibility, but here are two that do: https://mushroomobserver.org/381748 and https://www.messiah.edu/...
The first three images show a small cluster on a stump, and the last two images show terrestrial sporocarps within several feet of the stump that are somewhat behind in development. I theorize that the slightly different timing of sporocarp development resulting from the apparent colonization different substrates could be of benefit to the organism. It could result in a longer period of spore dispersal, thus increasing the chances of peak spore release and favorable weather conditions for optimal dispersal coinciding.
